[h1]The font-size Property [/h1]

You can also use numerical values in [b]pixels[/b] or [b]ems[/b] to manipulate font size. 
Setting the font size in pixel values ([b]px[/b]) is a good choice when you need pixel accuracy, and it gives you full control over the text size. 
The [b]em[/b] size unit is another way to set the font size ([b]em [/b]is a relative size unit). It allows all major browsers to resize the text. If you haven't set the font size anywhere on the page, then it is the browser default size, which is [b]16px[/b]. 

To calculate the em size, just use the following formula: [b]em = pixels / 16[/b]
[b]For example: [/b] [code format="css" codeId="512"]h1 {
   font-size: 20[b]px[/b];
}[/code]
[code format="css" codeId="513"]h1 {
   font-size: 1.25[b]em[/b]; 
}[/code]
Both of the examples will produce the same result in the browser, because [b]20/16=1.25em[/b].
[note]Try different combinations of text size and page zooming in a variety of browsers to ensure that the text remains readable.[/note]
